<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="194" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,151,176]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Without dissecting male specimens, 
<taxonomicName box="[746,858,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Singilis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="194" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burtoni" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[746,858,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">S. burtoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[867,932,151,176]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[867,932,151,176]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
could be rather difficult to distinguish from other small sized species of this group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="194" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,223,248]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Description.</emphasis>
Length 3.5–5.0 mm. Yellowish red-brown, elytra with black, sinuous transverse band behind middle (
<figureCitation box="[244,312,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1933,1956]" captionTargetBox="[184,1415,435,1908]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[164,1429,429,1915]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Habitus of Singilis (s. str.): 7 — S. pusillus (Peringuey, 1896) Lectotype; 8 — S. pusillus (Johannesburg, RSA); 9 — S. burtoni sp. n., Holotype; 10 — S. africaorientalis africaorientalis sp. n. Holotype; 11 — S. africaorientalis kenyacus ssp. n., Holotype; 12 — S. paganeli sp. n. Holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265438/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Head and clypeus mat, with strongl isodiametrical microsculpture. Head irregularly and deeply punctate, punctures separated by 1 to 3 diameters. Eyes large and bulging.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Pronotum 1.2–1.3 times as wide as head, 1.37–1.45 times as wide as long, widest behind marginal setae. Anterior margin straight, anterior angles effaced, sides regularly rounded, weakly sinuate or almost straigth at base, posterior angles rectangular. Punctation coarse and deep, as that on head or denser. Lateral margin flat, punctate, explanate in basal half. Basal grooves indistinct, flat. Microsculpture strong, irregular. Surface mat.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Elytra suboval, 1.5 times as long as wide, with polygonal microsculpture. Striae deep and slightly punctate. Intervals convex at base, weakly convex at apices.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[151,1208,583,608]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Propleuron coarsely rugose towards coxae, mes- and metepisterna with strong microsculpture.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,416,620,645]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Claws with 5 teeth.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Abdominal sterna smooth, shiny, with long sparse pubescence. Propleuron coarsely rugose towards coxae, mes- and metepisterna strongly microsculptured.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[325,411,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1602,1625]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,202,1570]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1581]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 28. Aedeagus of Singilis (s. str.): 25 — S. cribricollis (Peringuey, 1904) (Zambia); 26 — S. pusillus (Peringuey, 1898) (Stockpoort, RSA); 27 — S. burtoni sp. n., Holotype; 28 — S. paganeli sp. n. Holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265442/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
). Aedeagal median lobe moderately broad, euventral surface almost straight between basal bulb and downturned apex. Internal sac with two groups of small spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,412,799,824]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">Name derivation.</emphasis>
Named after Sir Richard Francis Burton (
<date box="[922,1053,799,824]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194" value="1821" valueMax="1890">
1821 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[979,993,799,824]" pageId="11" pageNumber="194">–</emphasis>
1890
</date>
), a British explorer, geographer, translator, writer, soldier, orientalist, cartographer, ethnologist, spy, linguist, poet, fencer, and diplomat. He was the first European to see Lake Tanganyika.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
